<div id="review_3651572589" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3651572589" />
    <a title="Irene" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/36459924-irene"><img alt="Irene" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1627675581p2/36459924.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3651572589?book_show_action=true">Nov 18, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Irene" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Irene" href="/user/show/36459924-irene">Irene</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/36459924-irene?shelf=regency-romances-and-bodice-rippers">regency-romances-and-bodice-rippers</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3651572589" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11635520397716821488">I&apos;ve noticed that if I&apos;m not hooked on the first page of an Amanda Quick novel, odds are I won&apos;t enjoy it. The times that I&apos;ve tried to make an honest go, it never seems to get into its stride. <br/><br/>Scandal, fortunately, is one that hooked me. <br/><br/>I think this hooked/not hooked feeling is heightened in Amanda Quick&apos;s work because she is so formulaic. And in its purest form, her formula is great, and no one else can do it like her! And in its worst form, it is, most oftentimes, an uninspired mystery with </span>
  <span id="freeText11635520397716821488" style="display:none">I've noticed that if I'm not hooked on the first page of an Amanda Quick novel, odds are I won't enjoy it. The times that I've tried to make an honest go, it never seems to get into its stride. <br /><br />Scandal, fortunately, is one that hooked me. <br /><br />I think this hooked/not hooked feeling is heightened in Amanda Quick's work because she is so formulaic. And in its purest form, her formula is great, and no one else can do it like her! And in its worst form, it is, most oftentimes, an uninspired mystery with lukewarm romance. <br /><br />You also have to love her couple, which is often a very traditional and overbearing hero who has to overcome his need to be in control all the time, and a free spirit smart cookie who is unafraid of her man but sees the good in him when no one else can. I love Emily or "Elf" as Simon calls her because she spoke her mind and was open with her emotions. One wonderful scene is when Simon apologizes to Emily for being grumpy in bed and Emily acknowledges why he acted that way and says, it was fun when we got there! I also loved her constant harping about their metaphysical connection, which is a hilarious little bit. <br /><br />I really, really enjoyed the fact that there was no mystery plot. I also felt that this wasn't as light as Quick's other works that I've read that can almost have a manic lightness to it, and I think this is why I felt this romance was more steamy than what I usually expect from Amanda Quick. I don't really expect sexy from her work, even though there are love scenes, but I did feel some scenes were quite sexy so that was a nice bonus!</span>
  <a data-text-id="11635520397716821488" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


